phers made their women saints walk on water, resurrect the dead, or consecrate the Eucharist, they also curbed the power of women by teaching that the daughters of Eve must make their bodies impenetrable through militant chastity or spiritual exile and must eradicate self-indulgence through ascetic attire or philanthropy. The windows the sacred fiction of holy women open on the past are far from transparent; driven by both literary invention and moral imperative, the stories they tell helped shape Western gender constructs that have survived into modern times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistorydTo 1500. 0aChristian hagiographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristian women saintsvBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian women saintsvBiography. 0aChristian women saintsxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in ChristianityxEarly church. 0aWomen in ChristianityxHistoryxEarly churchdca. 30-600. 0aWomen in ChristianityxHistoryxMiddle Agesd600-1500. 0aWomen in ChristianityxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aWomen in ChristianityxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aWomen in ChristianityxMiddle Ages. 4aAncient Studies. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 4aReligion. 4aReligious Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220167340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812201673.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Coll